english:
  title: Official Proclamation Appointing Choe Bu to the Position of Silver-Seal Grand Commandant of Light, Concurrent Vice-President of the Privy Council, and Right Attendant of the Palace
  author: Lee Kyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your station stands but one degree below the imperial threshold, your lineage closely bound to the forbidden halls. The weighty matters of state—those schemes and secrets—few of my ministers are privileged to hear. Though I trust and employ a man for his talents, I select through countless trials before conferring his rank.

    Officer Choe Bu: Your virtue stands as a model for all men. Generation upon generation, your house has kept the scholar's way. You unite keen judgment with broad vision, possess both learning and prudent counsel—bearing the full measure of a great minister. Your scholarship and conduct are without flaw—you embody your ancestor's noble spirit.

    Once you held authority over the southern provinces as inspector, and there you rekindled that ancient will to purify the realm. Rebellious brigands dared to harbor forbidden ambitions, their numbers swelling like branches multiplying. Had we not acted swiftly in that moment, their roots would have grown unshakeable. Through your strategy, you broke their edge before it hardened, allowing our forces an easy victory. Yet though your strength bore the weight of this triumph, another claimed the laurel. You received no reward, only whispered reproach—a lament even to the discerning, and one I too perceive.

    Therefore I have raised you from the ranks of the lesser ministers and directly conferred upon you the third rank. From the western library, you have offered counsel like bitter medicine, repeatedly speaking truth to power. From the southern tribunal, you have wielded the austere authority of frost and snow. As commander of the frontier garrison, your fierce presence keeps the barbarian hordes at our borders' edge. As director of selection, you have gathered the finest talents—phoenixes and dragons now flock to your gate. Truly yours is a talent beyond the common measure, deserving advancement that breaks all protocol.

    Thus I appoint you to command the military bureau and grant you the concurrent honor of imperial attendant. Your ascent surpasses all others—some might call it an exceptional promotion. Yet when I measure your abilities and renown against this honor, I find it still insufficient to your worth. I therefore specially appoint you Silver-Seal Grand Commandant of Light, Concurrent Vice-President of the Privy Council, and Right Attendant of the Palace.

    Hear me: I liken myself to metal unworked; you shall be my master craftsman. Be the rudder and sail, that I may cross the vast waters. Honor these words and serve faithfully the mandate of my favor.
  footnotes:
    - This is an official proclamation (관고, officially-promulgated edict) conferring honors and offices upon Choe Bu, a historical figure of the Goryeo period.
    - The 'yellow threshold' (황비) and 'forbidden halls' (자금) are classical terms for the imperial court and its innermost chambers.
    - The metaphor of the final passage—likening the ruler to unworked metal and the minister to a craftsman, with the minister as rudder and sail—draws on ancient Chinese philosophical imagery of harmonious rulership.
